"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129066","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-06-11","<p>The Office for Product Safety and Standards (OPSS) was set up in January 2018 to boost the UK’s product safety regime and provide national leadership on product safety matters. OPSS currently has access to my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State’s powers under the General Product Safety Regulations 2005. The Government has laid in draft an Order to ensure that OPSS powers reflect those available to other enforcement authorities under the Consumer Rights Act 2015. We will consult on whether further powers are necessary in due course.</p><p> </p><p>OPSS has additional funding on product safety of around £12m this year and the Department will consider OPSS funding requirements for future years in preparation for the next spending review.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-06-11T15:57:09.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129066/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129066/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-06-03","Consumer Goods: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to ensure that the Office for Product Safety and Standards has the (a) powers and (b) resources necessary to issue guidance and protect consumers effectively.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","259354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129067","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-06-11","<p>Local Authorities are independent from central government and are responsible for their own finances and funding decisions, accountable to their local electorates.</p><p>Government identified the need for national leadership and co-ordination of the product safety system and established the Office for Product Safety and Standards (OPSS) in January 2018 to fulfil this role.</p><p>OPSS has built capability to lead on national product safety issues. This includes commissioning a strategic research programme; setting up arrangements to deal with national product safety incidents; and forming a trading standards co-ordination unit to support the work that Local Authorities carry out on product safety in their local areas.</p><p>As part of its support for Local Authority Trading Standards, OPSS has made available £600,000 this year to Local Authorities for product safety testing, trained over 700 trading standards staff from 211 Local Authorities and provided scientific and technical support to increase Trading Standards capability on product safety regulation.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-06-11T15:57:39.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129067/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129067/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-06-03","Consumer Goods: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of reductions in funding on local authorities capacity to enforce product safety measures.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","259355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129068","Department for International Trade","false","2019-06-06","<p>Article 17 of the Export Control Order 2008 sets out the scope of controls applying to goods in transit or being transhipped. As Saudi Arabia is neither an embargoed destination nor a destination subject to stricter transit controls under the Order, a transhipment licence would not be required for military goods provided certain conditions are met. These conditions are principally that the goods were legally exported from the country of export (in this case, Belgium) and that they remain in the UK for a period of less than 30 days.</p><p> </p><p>We have no reason to believe these conditions were not met and therefore no transhipment licence was required.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-06-06T15:24:41.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129068/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129068/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-06-03","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to M/V Bahri Yanbu which moored at Tilbury docks around 7 May 2019 carrying cargo destined for Saudi Arabia, whether the Government determined whether that vessel was carrying licensable goods that required (a) a Standard Individual Transhipment Licence and (b) an Open General Transhipment Licence; and whether the Government issued Standard Individual Transhipment Licences for that shipment.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","259391"
