"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129243","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-06-06","<p>NHS England nationally commissions Gender Identity Services. In April 2019, NHS England began a process of national procurement to determine which organisations are best able to deliver adult gender dysphoria services in the future. The process of procurement is open to organisations that currently host a gender dysphoria clinic as well as new market entrants. The outcome of the process is expected to be known by the autumn of 2019.</p><p>Separately, NHS England has announced its intention to establish a number of pilot services across England from 2019/20 that will evaluate the extent to which gender dysphoria services can be delivered by trained clinical teams in local primary care or community health settings. If evaluated positively, NHS England will consider how to extend the new models to other parts of the country.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-06-06T15:22:45.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129243/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129243/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-06-03","Gender Recognition: Clinics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department plans to open more NHS gender identity clinics in England.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","259020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129244","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-06-06","<p>The Department has no plans to review this guidance.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-06-06T15:34:03.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129244/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129244/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-06-03","Gender Recognition: Clinics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has plans to change the guidelines that state that trans patients who seek private healthcare as a result of long waiting times in order to receive treatment and medication will remain eligible for NHS-funded treatments.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","259021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129245","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-06-10","<p>The average length of time a Band 3-5 prison officer working in their role, for those in post as at 31st March 2019 is 10.1 years.</p><p> </p><p>Average working time in role is calculated by taking total length of service of all prison officers divided by the number of prison officers (Headcount), as at 31st March 2019.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2019-06-10T15:01:33.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129245/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129245/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-06-03","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of time is that a prison officer remains working in their role.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","259329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129246","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-06-11","<p>As Chair of the High-Level Stakeholder Working Group on EU Exit, Universities, Research and Innovation, I regularly engage with senior representatives from UK universities, academies and businesses to discuss issues of common interest regarding the UK’s exit from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>I continue to support positive discussions with representatives of these organisations on how best to maintain UK collaboration, including with a wide range of European umbrella organisations.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","259208","2019-06-11T15:55:24.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129246/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129246/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-06-03","Universities: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support the future engagement of UK universities with CESAER, LERU, EUA, the Guild, and other European University Associations, in order to maintain levels of collaboration in research, teaching and best practice after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","259207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129247","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-06-11","<p>Clean Growth is at the heart of this Government’s modern Industrial Strategy. There are currently 400,000 jobs in the low carbon economy, with the ambition to have 2 million by 2030.</p><p> </p><p>We’ve injected £2.5 billion into low-carbon innovation and earlier this year struck a deal with the offshore wind industry, which will see up to £40 billion worth of infrastructure investment in the UK, creating clean, green electricity, good jobs and sustained growth across the UK. Under the Offshore Wind Sector Deal, industry aims to more than triple the number of ‘green collar’ jobs in the sector to 27,000 by 2030, up from the current figure of 7,200.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2019-06-11T15:54:37.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129247/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129247/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129247/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-06-03","Renewable Energy: Job Creation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to create more jobs in the renewable energy sector.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","259056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129248","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-06-06","<p>The Centre of Excellence is currently the subject of a feasibility study which will provide Ministers with options on timings, scope and costs. At this stage, no decision has been made on when the Centre of Excellence will begin operation.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-06-06T13:05:53.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129248/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129248/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-06-03","Centre of Excellence for Human Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the Centre of Excellence for Human Security will be established.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","259117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129249","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-10","<p>In line with usual practice, the Government’s intention would be to publish an impact assessment on our leasehold reforms as part of taking primary legislation through Parliament.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","259418","2019-06-10T15:52:43.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129249/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129249/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-03","Leasehold: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department will publish an impact assessment on the proposed reforms to the leasehold system.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","259417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129250","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-10","<p>In line with usual practice, the Government’s intention would be to publish an impact assessment on our leasehold reforms as part of taking primary legislation through Parliament.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","259417","2019-06-10T15:52:43.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129250/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129250/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-03","Ground Rent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to publish an impact assessment of the proposal to introduce a £10 cap on all future ground rents in the leasehold market.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","259418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129251","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-10","<p>On 1 April 2018, the Government published its response document <em>Protecting Consumers in the Letting and Managing Agent Market, </em> which outlined its consideration for a mandatory code of practice in the property agent sector. The Government is committed to introducing a mandatory of code practice for managing agents who administer leasehold contracts on behalf of landlords. Where a landlord undertakes the administration of a leasehold contract themselves, they will be obliged to meet the statutory requirements of the forthcoming code.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-06-10T15:53:18.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129251/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129251/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-03","Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of introducing a mandatory code of practice for landlords to improve standards in the leasehold sector.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","259419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129252","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-10","<p>The Government ran a technical consultation ‘Implementing reforms to the leasehold system’ during 15 October 2018 to 26 November 2018, and will be publishing the response shortly. The consultation received over 1,200 replies from a broad range of stakeholders.</p><p>During the consultation and analysis period, my Department has engaged extensively with freeholders, leaseholders, consumer groups, and other professionals on a wide range of leasehold reform issues including limiting ground rents to £10 per annum.</p><p>In particular, my Department held round table meetings with industry (building developers and investors), and leaseholders and consumer groups in November 2018.</p><p>The Secretary of State also met with developers and investors on 15 November 2018, and leaseholders on 29 January 2019. A full list of ministerial meetings is published at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data</a> and is updated regularly.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-06-10T15:51:37.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129252/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129252/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129252/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-03","Ground Rent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what (a) meetings, (b) correspondence and (c) other engagement his Department has had with (i) consumer groups, (ii) freeholders and (iii) leaseholders to discuss the proposal for a £10 cap on future ground rents.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","259420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129253","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-06-11","<p>As Chair of the High-Level Stakeholder Working Group on EU Exit, Universities, Research and Innovation, I regularly engage with senior representatives from UK universities, academies and businesses to discuss issues of common interest regarding the UK’s exit from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>I continue to support positive discussions with representatives of these organisations on how best to maintain UK collaboration, including with a wide range of European umbrella organisations.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","259207","2019-06-11T15:55:24.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129253/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129253/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129253/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-06-03","Universities: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support the future engagement of UK universities with European University Associations such as CESAER, LERU, EUA, the Guild, in order to maintain levels of collaboration in research, teaching and best practice.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","259208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129254","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-06-10","<p>As people live longer than ever before, sometimes with complex care needs, we need to ensure the social care system is sustainable in the longer term. The Green Paper remains a priority for the Government. We are continuing to work on it closely, taking the time to consult with key stakeholders and take their feedback into consideration. As such, it will be published at the earliest opportunity.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-06-10T15:19:14.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129254/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129254/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129254/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-06-03","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he plans to bring forward a social care Green Paper.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","259057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129255","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-06-12","<p>It is right and proper that Government reviews the whistleblowing framework, however we believe that it would be premature to conduct a review at this time. Instead we should allow the existing changes that we have introduced to embed and build the necessary evidence of their impact to support a review in due course.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-06-12T16:21:27.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129255/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129255/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129255/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-06-03","Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 19 March 2019 to Question 909885 on the Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998, what progress his Department has made in planning for the assessment of the recent reforms to the legislative framework of protection for workers.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","259315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129256","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-06-11","<p>The total number of Band 3-5 Prison Officers recruited in Wales in 2018 was 219. 191 (87%) of those staff are still working for the Prison Service based on the latest available data.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2019-06-11T16:49:01.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129256/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129256/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129256/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-06-03","Prison Officers: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of prison officers recruited in 2018 in Wales are still working for the prison service.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","259330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129257","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-06-06","<p>Universal Credit is a means tested system of support and where claimants have income available to meet their everyday living costs, such as maternity allowance, it is right that their entitlement to UC is adjusted accordingly (as currently is the case with other DWP legacy means tested working age benefits).</p><p>Statutory maternity pay is paid by an employer and is a form of earnings. As a result, statutory maternity pay is therefore subject to the work allowance and tapering within Universal Credit, as are other earnings.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-06-06T16:33:04.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129257/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129257/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129257/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-03","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will review the merits of the higher deduction from universal credit payments for maternity allowance than for maternity pay.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","259377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129258","Treasury","false","2019-06-11","<p>The Government has been clear that the mis-selling of Payment Protection Insurance (PPI) was wrong, and affected consumers should receive redress.</p><p> </p><p>The deadline for making PPI claims and supporting consumers in making PPI claims are matters for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), which is operationally independent from Government. The question has therefore been passed on to the FCA who will reply directly to the honourable member. A copy of their response will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","259409","2019-06-11T13:45:31.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129258/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129258/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-06-03","Insurance: Misrepresentation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps (a) his Department and (b) the FCA is taking to raise awareness of the ability of the next-of-kin of deceased persons to bring a complaint for the mis-selling of PPI and their right to reclaim.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","259408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129259","Treasury","false","2019-06-11","<p>The Government has been clear that the mis-selling of Payment Protection Insurance (PPI) was wrong, and affected consumers should receive redress.</p><p> </p><p>The deadline for making PPI claims and supporting consumers in making PPI claims are matters for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), which is operationally independent from Government. The question has therefore been passed on to the FCA who will reply directly to the honourable member. A copy of their response will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","259408","2019-06-11T13:45:31.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129259/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129259/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-06-03","Insurance: Misrepresentation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment (a) his Department and (b) the FCA has made of the potential merits of excluding vulnerable consumers, such as those claiming on behalf of a deceased person, from the deadline for claims for the mis-selling of PPI.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","259409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129260","Home Office","false","2019-06-06","<p>For all police forces in England and Wales, shoplifting is recorded under a single crime code according to the Home Office counting rules; the Theft Act 1968.</p><p>The Home Office holds information on all offences recorded by police, including the offence of Shoplifting, which is published by Police Force Area (PFA). Information on the number of shoplifting offences recorded in each financial year from April 2012 to December 2018 can be found in the Open Data tables, which can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</a></p><p>An impact assessment was carried out for the crime threshold of £200 on levels of crime, which can be found here: <br><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/252650/Annex_A_Overarching_IA_Lords.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/252650/Annex_A_Overarching_IA_Lords.pdf</a></p><p>The Government recognises the cost and disruption that shoplifting can cause to businesses, as well as to communities and consumers. It is important that retailers continue to report incidents of shoplifting and violence to the police so that effective action can be taken against offenders.</p><p>The Minister for Crime, Safeguarding and Vulnerability co-chairs the National Retail Crime Steering Group which brings together Government, enforcement and key retail partners to identify and tackle the issues facing retailers in England and Wales. The Group’s key areas of focus include work to tackle shop theft and work to address violence and abuse toward retail staff.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","259107 ; 259108","2019-06-06T14:55:02.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129260/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129260/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-06-03","Shoplifting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, under what different categories may shoplifting be recorded; and whether there are regional differences in that recording.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","259106"
